Release Note:
What's New
We have a new JSON field ✨, a bunch of new learning resources, and plenty of under the hood optimisations in this big release. 💪 
JSON Field 👩🏻‍💻
Thanks to the new module field, you can now represent JSON blobs in your backend. Check out the link to learn more.  
module
More Learning Resources 🧑‍🏫
In addition to the JSON one above, we added new examples for: 

Setting link for fields.
link with custom queries and mutations.

We also published a tutorial that shows you link. The end result is an app with a queryable GraphQL endpoint based on your Keystone schema that you can run live on Vercel – for free! 🚀 
module deprecated with improvements to module 🤹‍♂️
We deprecated the module GraphQL filter and updated the module GraphQL filter with an improved API.
Previously a module list's module query would have the argument:
module
The new API gives it the argument:
module
where
```graphql
input UserOrderByInput {
  id: OrderDirection
  name: OrderDirection
  score: OrderDirection
}
enum OrderDirection {
  asc
  desc
}
```
Rather than writing module you now write module. You can also order by multiple fields, e.g. module.
Note: each module must have exactly one key, or else an error will be returned.
module replaced with module 🔧
We removed module in favour of a module option to the module function.
Previously, module would be used to wrap the module argument:
```typescript
import { config, createSchema, list } from '@keystone-next/keystone/schema';
import { statelessSessions, withAuthData } from '@keystone-next/keystone/session';
import { text, password, checkbox } from '@keystone-next/fields';
import { createAuth } from '@keystone-next/auth';
const { withAuth } = createAuth({
  listKey: 'User',
  identityField: 'email',
  secretField: 'password',
});
const session = statelessSessions({ secret: '-- EXAMPLE COOKIE SECRET; CHANGE ME --' });
export default withAuth(
  config({
    lists: createSchema({
module
})
);
```
Now, the fields to populate are configured on module in module, and module is completely removed. 🧹 
```typescript
import { config, createSchema, list } from '@keystone-next/keystone/schema';
import { statelessSessions } from '@keystone-next/keystone/session';
import { text, password, checkbox } from '@keystone-next/fields';
import { createAuth } from '@keystone-next/auth';
const { withAuth } = createAuth({
  listKey: 'User',
  identityField: 'email',
  secretField: 'password',
  sessionData: 'id isAdmin',
});
const session = statelessSessions({ secret: '-- EXAMPLE COOKIE SECRET; CHANGE ME --' });
export default withAuth(
  config({
    lists: createSchema({
module
})
);
```
More consistent and predictable module, module, and module mutations 🧘‍♀️
We fixed the behaviour of module, module, and module mutations to be consistent and predictable.
Previously, these mutations could return items in an arbitrary order. They now return items in the same order they were provided to the mutation.
Previously, if there was an error (e.g. validation) on one or more of the items – the return value would be module and a single top level error would be returned. The state of the database in this case was non-deterministic.
The new behaviour is to return values for all items created, with module values for those that had errors. These errors are returned in the module array and have paths which correctly point to the module values in the returned array. All the valid operations will be completed, leaving the database in a deterministic state.
Previously, if items were filtered out by declarative access control, then no error would be returned, and only those accessible items would be returned. Now the returned data will contain module values for those items which couldn't accessed, and the module array will contain errors with paths which correctly point to the module values in the returned array.
Previously, if static access control denied access to the mutation, then module was returned, and a single module was returned. Now, an array of modules is returned, with a separate error for each object. This makes the behaviour of static and declarative access control consistent.
Counts Improved 🔢
The GraphQL field module generated for module relationships has been deprecated in favour of a new field module, which directly returns the count.
A module relationship field would have the following field added to the API:
module
Prisma updated to module ⬆️
We've updated our Prisma dependency from module to module! Check out the link for more details.
